I'm a Nintendo fan since forever so, despite the fact that recently the company has been releasing at least one game of this brand per year not investing enough time and resources for a good development, I decided to buy this game anyway. I have mixed feeling about this game, because overall I think it's somewhat good: it has an entertaining plot with a decent insight into the characters, an explorable open map and the concept of time paradoxes, that is interesting. Sadly, the flaws are too many and too big to simply enjoy this game: childish difficulty, lazy new Pokémon designs (some of them are good but for the most part they just look like they're made by people with a passion for memes and no imagination) and an horrible and sloppy graphic.

Most recent game I remember not enjoying was "The Outer Worlds", by Obsidian Entertainment.
The game was overly hyped before its release, since it was being developed by people who had worked on a very good RPG game, popular for having the best story out of that game's last three installments (Fallout New Vegas).
As such, I expected good writing in "The Outer Worlds", or at least anything unique on it that could hold me in and entertain. Instead I got your average sci-fi "Rich people are always the evil cruel monsters! The rebels were actually the good guys!" story that felt too much like a clear propaganda. That combined with the fact the NPCs all had the same punchable smug face, and gameplay being "Meh" as a typical "adventure FPS".
The issue wasn't the game being political, the issue was the game was very poorly written accompanied by clearly forced choices, with a tedious repetitive gameplay, soul-less characters, and a horrible inventory management.

I felt like I was doing a chore the entire game, without any real improvements throughout it.

The game was Batman: Arkham Knights. After playing Spiderman I was really excited to play this game, but it turned out to be really satisfactory. The most recent game that I've played is CS:GO. In fact, you could say I'm a veteran player, as I've played that game for over 3000 hours (according to my Steam profile). So me and my teammates played a competitive match on a map called "Anubis" (kind of a new map), and we managed to win 16-13 (that match took around 40 minutes). The best thing about competitive games is the "flow" state that they allow you to enter. That is something I usually experience a few times per match. Especially in emotionally charged situations. That "flow" makes me somehow connected to the game on a psychic level. My field of view shrinks a bit, which lets me focus on the game more, my reaction time gets way faster, and I completely cut off all the stimuli outside of the game. You should read about that, it's sort of a common thing for pro players, and that might be helpful for your study.

I play video games very regularly, in long sessions. The last time I played a computer game for at least 20 minutes was yesterday. My friends and I played GTA Online. We come back to this game from time to time to spend time together. The game is not about some predetermined activities, and above all about spending time together, where the game is simply the background.
This time we restocked parcel warehouses to later sell them as a group. I felt great during these activities, but it was mainly because of this opportunity to interact with friends. The gameplay itself would seem boring to most.
There are many such games in which I immerse myself and feel full immersion, such as Red Dead Redemption, in which I spent hundreds of hours and completed this game many times.
I also like games that are seemingly boring to most people, such as ETS. When I'm driving in ETS, I like to listen to the radio and watch the scenery. It is also a time when I can talk to someone, e.g. on discord, or watch a video on YouTube or Netflix.
Anyway, games are all about having fun. The point is that every game user should be able to use them in any way that makes them happy, as long as it does not interfere with the fun of other people.
